295
00:17:29,120 --> 00:17:34,120
not to say that green capital doesn't have its own problems,

296
00:17:34,120 --> 00:17:39,120
but certainly in terms of curbing fossil fuel consumption

297
00:17:40,280 --> 00:17:43,760
as fast as possible, which is necessary

298
00:17:43,760 --> 00:17:48,760
for any chance of meeting one and a half degree warming limit,

299
00:17:49,160 --> 00:17:54,160
we need to promote green capital,

300
00:17:54,720 --> 00:17:59,720
defeat fossil capital and form a global alliance

301
00:17:59,720 --> 00:18:00,920
with green capital.

302
00:18:00,920 --> 00:18:03,760
So I agree with you, there are incentives

303
00:18:03,760 --> 00:18:05,600
that are necessary.

304
00:18:05,600 --> 00:18:09,080
We probably agree more than you think,

305
00:18:09,080 --> 00:18:11,120
and I'll be quiet now.

306
00:18:11,120 --> 00:18:14,760
I'll jump in, I'll say that from this angle,

307
00:18:14,760 --> 00:18:16,800
I see a set of intersecting,

308
00:18:16,800 --> 00:18:19,320
interlocking global crises,

309
00:18:19,320 --> 00:18:22,760
that all are linked to the history of the last 30 years

310
00:18:22,760 --> 00:18:25,120
in globalization 1.0.

311
00:18:25,120 --> 00:18:28,520
And we deregulated financial markets.

312
00:18:28,520 --> 00:18:31,240
We decided not to move away from oil and gas

313
00:18:31,240 --> 00:18:34,760
in the United States, at least we decided that in Europe,

314
00:18:34,760 --> 00:18:38,920
the approach to Russia was about market liberalization,

315
00:18:38,920 --> 00:18:42,760
the idea that interdependence would turn Russia

316
00:18:42,760 --> 00:18:44,920
into a liberal democracy.

317
00:18:44,920 --> 00:18:48,000
And just on that last, and then Germany in particular,

318
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:50,480
in Europe became very dependent on natural gas

319
00:18:50,480 --> 00:18:52,560
for reasons that are complex.

320
00:18:53,600 --> 00:18:57,080
But in some ways, you could ask whether that focus

321
00:18:57,080 --> 00:18:59,560
on market liberalization,

322
00:18:59,560 --> 00:19:01,720
does that humor aimed back in ways

323
00:19:01,720 --> 00:19:05,760
that have contributed to the current crisis in Ukraine?

324
00:19:05,760 --> 00:19:07,120
I'm not sure that that's right,

325
00:19:07,120 --> 00:19:08,680
but that's a question that's on my mind

326
00:19:08,680 --> 00:19:09,840
that I'll put that there.

327
00:19:11,680 --> 00:19:15,020
Can I add a little bit on incentives as well?

328
00:19:16,200 --> 00:19:19,160
Of course, incentives are important.

329
00:19:19,160 --> 00:19:21,680
The reason we're in, the mess we're in right now

330
00:19:21,680 --> 00:19:23,920
is precisely because we've been sending people

331
00:19:23,920 --> 00:19:25,360
the wrong incentives.

332
00:19:26,320 --> 00:19:29,400
You discharge CO2 into the air,

333
00:19:29,400 --> 00:19:32,280
that has costs on everybody.

334
00:19:32,280 --> 00:19:36,000
Nobody pays an extra fee for the right to do that.

335
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:38,520
We could do it without charge now.

336
00:19:38,520 --> 00:19:41,800
We never should have allowed that incentive

337
00:19:41,800 --> 00:19:44,040
to remain in place.

338
00:19:44,040 --> 00:19:47,400
We need to make massive public investment now

339
00:19:47,400 --> 00:19:50,000
in order to achieve climate stability.

340
00:19:50,000 --> 00:19:52,680
And there's very little time left

341
00:19:52,680 --> 00:19:56,680
to meet the objective of avoiding temperature increases

342
00:19:56,680 --> 00:19:58,880
greater than 1.5 degrees Celsius,

343
00:19:58,880 --> 00:20:02,880
which read David Wallace Wells' book.

344
00:20:02,880 --> 00:20:05,680
If you haven't, there are grim fates in store

345
00:20:05,680 --> 00:20:09,040
for us in every country,

346
00:20:09,040 --> 00:20:11,480
if we let temperature rise more than that.

347
00:20:11,480 --> 00:20:13,280
So we've got to act quickly.

348
00:20:13,280 --> 00:20:16,680
And I think the investments we need to make,

349
00:20:16,680 --> 00:20:18,880
many can come in the private sector.

350
00:20:18,880 --> 00:20:22,920
We can guide them as we have in the past

351
00:20:22,920 --> 00:20:27,920
with subsidies for renewable energy investments and the like.

352
00:20:27,920 --> 00:20:32,920
There is now a very exciting new technology

353
00:20:33,880 --> 00:20:38,880
developed by ClimbWorks in Switzerland

354
00:20:39,240 --> 00:20:41,000
to suck carbon out of the air

355
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:43,680
and turn it into a carbon-based slurry

356
00:20:43,680 --> 00:20:45,160
that you pump deep underground.

357
00:20:45,160 --> 00:20:47,240
And it's very expensive now,

358
00:20:47,240 --> 00:20:51,360
but we're on a track to have the cost of that come down

359
00:20:51,360 --> 00:20:54,320
rapidly enough to where it too could make a difference.

360
00:20:54,320 --> 00:20:57,880
But all this is going to require an enormous amount of money.

361
00:20:57,880 --> 00:21:00,880
We've got an enormous amount of money.

362
00:21:00,880 --> 00:21:03,440
That's not the problem.

363
00:21:03,440 --> 00:21:07,040
The problem is to persuade people to part

364
00:21:07,040 --> 00:21:09,960
with what they're using the money for now

365
00:21:09,960 --> 00:21:12,720
and to use it instead for these other things,

366
00:21:12,720 --> 00:21:14,600
that if we don't use it for them,

367
00:21:14,600 --> 00:21:16,600
there's not going to be a future for us.

368
00:21:16,600 --> 00:21:20,160
And so I think that means if you want to be practical,

369
00:21:20,160 --> 00:21:22,800
looking to the top of the income pyramid,

370
00:21:22,800 --> 00:21:25,840
there's enormous resources there.

371
00:21:25,840 --> 00:21:28,480
We've been hearing about wealth taxes

372
00:21:28,480 --> 00:21:31,640
and how small the bite they need to take

373
00:21:31,640 --> 00:21:35,120
in order to generate enormous pools of resources

374
00:21:35,120 --> 00:21:39,800
to invest in these public projects that need to happen.

375
00:21:39,800 --> 00:21:43,560
I'm not worried about people lacking incentives

376
00:21:43,560 --> 00:21:47,760
to grow wealthy if they have to pay a little bit more in tax.

377
00:21:47,760 --> 00:21:51,080
There's a huge literature on the determinants

378
00:21:51,080 --> 00:21:52,480
of human flourishing.

379
00:21:52,480 --> 00:21:54,760
It's contentious.

380
00:21:54,760 --> 00:21:57,120
People argue about many of the findings in it.

381
00:21:57,120 --> 00:21:59,240
The one thing they don't argue about,

382
00:21:59,240 --> 00:22:03,400
the one really secure finding that's held up in every study

383
00:22:03,400 --> 00:22:05,360
is that beyond a certain point,

384
00:22:05,360 --> 00:22:07,240
and it's one we've long since passed,

385
00:22:07,240 --> 00:22:09,800
and most countries in the West have too,

386
00:22:09,800 --> 00:22:13,280
further increases in consumption

387
00:22:13,280 --> 00:22:17,280
serve only to raise the bar that we think of as adequate.

388
00:22:17,280 --> 00:22:20,800
So if all the mansions get 10% bigger,

389
00:22:20,800 --> 00:22:24,000
the people living in them aren't any happier,

390
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:26,760
any healthier than they were before.

391
00:22:26,760 --> 00:22:31,760
If the cars get bigger, people aren't only not happier.

392
00:22:31,960 --> 00:22:34,600
They're at more risk of death and injury.

393
00:22:34,600 --> 00:22:36,880
We burn up more fossil fuels.

394
00:22:36,880 --> 00:22:39,320
All of these things could be changed

395
00:22:39,320 --> 00:22:41,640
if we changed people's incentives,

396
00:22:41,640 --> 00:22:44,720
and we've got simple tax levers that can do that.

397
00:22:44,720 --> 00:22:47,280
So yes, incentives are important,

398
00:22:47,280 --> 00:22:51,880
and we've been steering people with the wrong incentives.

399
00:22:51,880 --> 00:22:54,520
Thus far, that's why we're in the best that we're in.

